  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Enhancing the protection rights of newly displaced children in Northern Shan State</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The impact of the intensified armed conflict since November 2016 on both IDPs and host communities in Northern Shan is severe, displacing an additional 4,000 people across the state. Many have experienced multiple displacements, have had to cross frontlines to find safety and face multiple barriers in accessing services. Violence against children, psychosocial distress, child labor, use and recruitment of children by armed forces/armed groups, separation of children from their families to ensure continued access to education and killing and maiming due to contamination by landmine and unexploded ordnance exposure are some of the major challenges children and families face. Men and boys are consistently targeted for recruitment into armed forces or armed groups and there are now few adult men in IDP camps. Women are therefore responsible for both domestic work and for generating family income. Additionally, drug and alcohol consumption in the men that remain has resulted in increased domestic violence. Girls are vulnerable to early marriage and trafficking.
This Save the Children (SC) intervention will provide emergency child protection programming for 1,830 people including 549 women, 366 men, 439 girls and 476 boys to prevent or mitigate the eminent violations of protection rights. This will be achieved through the provision of mobile psychosocial support, case management services, the enhancement of community capacities and networks (formal and informal), raising awareness of child protection minimum standards and child protection mainstreaming in humanitarian action with other key actors (KMSS, KBC and Metta). This approach focuses on both prevention and response, placing the protection of conflict affected populations at the forefront of the response. Communications with and the participation of affected people, conflict sensitivity, and gender sensitivity are prioritized in implementation. SC is committed to the Statement on Centrality of Protection in Humanitarian Action, endorsed by the Inter-Agency Standing Committee (IASC) Principals in 2013 as well as the United Nations &#x201C;Human Rights Up Front&#x201D; Plan of Action, which emphasizes the imperative for the United Nations to protect people, wherever they may be, in accordance with their human rights.</narrative>
  </description>
